# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-philadelphia-phillies-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1883 season was the first in the history of the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team was founded earlier in the year as a replacement for the Worcester franchise.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] It was the first year Philadelphia was represented in the National League since the original Athletics were disbanded in 1876 after refusing to finish the season.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The American Association's Philadelphia Athletics had been founded a year earlier.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team opened the year managed by Bob Ferguson; however, he was fired as manager after a disappointing 4–13 start and replaced by Blondie Purcell.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished the season 17–81, worst in the National League.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game ever on April 2, 1883, and defeated the amateur Manayunk Ashlands in an exhibition game by the score of 11–0 at Recreation Park.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies hosted Providence at Recreation Park in their first regular season game on May 1, 1883.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] One thousand fans saw John Coleman start the game for the Phillies and relinquish the first hit in the first inning to Providence first baseman Joe Start.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies scored first and took a three to zero lead into the eighth inning when Providence scored four times to win the game.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies would lose their first eleven games, and not win their first game at home in Philadelphia until June 6, 1883.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1884-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1884 season was the second in the history of the Philadelphia Quakers.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1885 Philadelphia Quakers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished with a record of 56–54, a distant third place in the National League, 30 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] On June 1, 1885, nearly 10,000 fans filled the Phillies' Recreation Park to see the Phillies face the New York Giants, with fans crowded down the right and left field foul lines.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1886-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1886 Philadelphia Phillies season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1886-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 71–43, 14 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **Philadelphia Quakers** team, also known as "the Phillies," opened its 1887 season by playing a home game in its new ballpark on Saturday, April 30 against the New York Giants.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] Multiple civic and business leaders were in attendance.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies held spring training in Savannah, Georgia, leaving Philadelphia on March 15, 1887 by train from Broad Street Station.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies trained in Savannah through March 25.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies opened their preseason City Series against the Athletics on April 4, 1887 at the Athletics' Jefferson Street Grounds.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] 9,183 tickets were sold to the game and an "immense crowd" turned out to see the Phillies win by a score of 10 to 2.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies moved into their new ballpark at 15th and Huntingdon Streets in April 1887.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The park was to have opened on April 4, 1887 for the City Series game against the Athletics but inclement weather delayed final construction.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game in the new ballpark on Saturday, April 30, 1887, the home opener against the New York Giants.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] 18,000 tickets were sold for the first game, with 13,000 in the stands and an additional 5,000 fans crowded onto the bicycle track which encircled the field and others in the terraces above left field.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] Philadelphia's Mayor Edwin Henry Fitler attended along with the city's political and business leadership, and many baseball leaders.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1888 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the 6th season in the history of the franchise and second season playing home games at National League Park at Broad and Huntingdon Streets.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies held spring training in Cape May, New Jersey from March 19, 1888, to March 30, 1888.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies stayed at the Chalfonte Hotel and practiced and played games games at the Cape May Athletic Park behind the hotel between Sewell and Benton Streets.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] When rain and snow barred outdoor work, Manager Harry Wright secured the use of the indoor Star Rink where the players practiced.
[src:1901-philadelphia-phillies-season/1901-philadelphia-phillies-season] The following lists the events of the **1901 Philadelphia Phillies season.** The Phillies finished second in the National League with a record of 83–57.
